41
00:02:10,764 --> 00:02:16,901
<i>and their disappointments. This is</i>
Seattle Medical: Road to Recovery.

42
00:02:18,405 --> 00:02:20,905
<i>Things have changed
since the shooting, sure.</i>

43
00:02:21,007 --> 00:02:25,493
For one thing, over the last
month, we have installed a number

44
00:02:25,596 --> 00:02:28,380
of new, uh, security measures.

45
00:02:28,482 --> 00:02:31,683
We're trying to make
it safer for the hospital,

46
00:02:31,785 --> 00:02:34,319
the doctors and the patients.

47
00:02:34,421 --> 00:02:36,221
- Come on!
- So, what...

48
00:02:36,323 --> 00:02:37,900
We go through this every
morning. It's me. I swear.

49
00:02:37,924 --> 00:02:41,176
I just... I have a different hair
color, that's all. It's... Chief!

50
00:02:41,278 --> 00:02:45,714
Chief, would you please... Would
you come tell them that I'm me? Please?

51
00:02:45,815 --> 00:02:47,382
Um...

52
00:02:47,484 --> 00:02:51,519
- Excuse me. What's going on?
- I just... Every day.

53
00:02:51,622 --> 00:02:54,472
Uh, we are fourth-year
surgical residents.

54
00:02:54,575 --> 00:02:57,559
And, uh, we're
friends. Good friends.

55
00:02:57,661 --> 00:03:03,548
It's pretty impossible to work this
closely and not become good friends.

56
00:03:03,650 --> 00:03:06,901
Can we call Respiratory
to get a vent down here?

57
00:03:07,003 --> 00:03:09,688
He's tachycardic
and hypotensive.

58
00:03:09,790 --> 00:03:13,592
Decreased breath sounds on
the left. Let's get a chest tube.

59
00:03:13,694 --> 00:03:15,774
- His blood pressure's dropping.
- Let's make sure...

60
00:03:15,813 --> 00:03:19,714
<i>Sure, going through something
like that, it's brought us closer.</i>

61
00:03:19,816 --> 00:03:21,583
Not that we
weren't close before.

62
00:03:21,685 --> 00:03:24,286
I mean, ask anyone. We're close.

63
00:03:24,404 --> 00:03:27,088
Dr. Yang and my wife
sometimes have sleepovers.

64
00:03:27,190 --> 00:03:29,391
In my bed, with me in it.

65
00:03:29,493 --> 00:03:32,377
<i>So, yeah. Yes. It's
brought us closer for sure.</i>

66
00:03:32,479 --> 00:03:35,229
- He needs a thoracotomy.
- Right, right.

67
00:03:35,332 --> 00:03:37,165
- Yes, please.
- I'll work the OR.

68
00:03:37,267 --> 00:03:38,850
Where's that ABG?

69
00:03:41,872 --> 00:03:43,238
Sterile drape.

70
00:03:43,340 --> 00:03:46,508
- Here. Take over
compressions. Great.
- I'll get it.

71
00:03:46,610 --> 00:03:51,112
<i>It's, uh, 7am. I've
been here two hours.</i>

72
00:03:51,214 --> 00:03:54,066
My interns, they
got here before that.

73
00:03:54,167 --> 00:03:58,570
They check on the patients and report
to me before I check on the patients,

74
00:03:58,672 --> 00:04:01,433
report to my attending.
Lily! I told you already.

75
00:04:01,475 --> 00:04:05,844
Turn it down or put in the headphones.
The rest of us don't have Bieber fever.

76
00:04:05,946 --> 00:04:09,681
Whatever that is.

77
00:04:09,783 --> 00:04:12,551
How have I changed
since the shooting?

78
00:04:12,652 --> 00:04:15,053
Um...

79
00:04:15,155 --> 00:04:17,822
I don't know.

80
00:04:17,924 --> 00:04:19,924
Oh, I got this.

81
00:04:24,431 --> 00:04:29,801
Today, I'm going back to Seattle
Grace for my colostomy reversal.

82
00:04:29,903 --> 00:04:33,204
Oh. Babe, did we remember
my robe and my fuzzy socks?

83
00:04:33,307 --> 00:04:37,442
Yes and yes. If by
"we," you mean me.

84
00:04:37,544 --> 00:04:39,411
Because you forgot.

85
00:04:39,513 --> 00:04:43,047
<i>I was supposed to get
this surgery months ago but,</i>

86
00:04:43,150 --> 00:04:46,968
well, the shooting
happened instead.

87
00:04:47,070 --> 00:04:50,588
- You have the parking ticket?
- Yeah, in my pocket.

88
00:04:54,795 --> 00:04:57,829
<i>I haven't been back to
the hospital since that day.</i>

89
00:04:57,931 --> 00:05:01,116
<i>I don't know how it
will feel to be back.</i>

90
00:05:01,218 --> 00:05:05,186
<i>That's right, it's
Portman. P-O-R-T-M-A-N.</i>

91
00:05:05,306 --> 00:05:07,773
And can you tell me where
I can get this validated?

92
00:05:07,875 --> 00:05:09,475
- I'll take care of it.
- Thanks.

93
00:05:13,681 --> 00:05:16,080
Hey, Dr. B.

94
00:05:16,183 --> 00:05:18,216
Oh!

95
00:05:18,319 --> 00:05:23,188
Yeah, I don't generally make
it a habit to hug my patients.

96
00:05:23,290 --> 00:05:26,041
<i>Yeah, well, when you get
paged 911, you don't walk.</i>

97
00:05:26,143 --> 00:05:28,126
<i>You never walk.</i>

98
00:05:29,196 --> 00:05:31,029
OK, talk.

99
00:05:34,335 --> 00:05:36,201
OK.

100
00:05:45,111 --> 00:05:48,012
God, I can't get past the
obstruction. Damn it. How long?

101
00:05:48,114 --> 00:05:49,754
- Five minutes.
- Damn it!

102
00:05:51,451 --> 00:05:53,452
Yes. Yes, do it now.

103
00:06:13,173 --> 00:06:15,613
No, no, no. Lily, Lily, I
know, I know this is scary.

104
00:06:15,709 --> 00:06:18,609
You stopped breathing. And
so we had to take you to the OR

105
00:06:18,711 --> 00:06:21,279
and put a tube in your neck
to help get you air. No, no.

106
00:06:21,381 --> 00:06:24,983
You can't talk, OK? But we called
your mom at work, and she's on her way.

107
00:06:25,085 --> 00:06:27,836
Lily was admitted with
respiratory distress last night.

108
00:06:27,938 --> 00:06:30,238
She has a growth
on her windpipe.

109
00:06:30,340 --> 00:06:32,724
It's benign, except for
there's nothing benign

110
00:06:32,826 --> 00:06:34,237
about something that's
blocking your airway.

111
00:06:34,261 --> 00:06:36,138
She's had surgeries
to remove it in the past,

112
00:06:36,162 --> 00:06:37,740
but it's aggressive.
It keeps recurring,

113
00:06:37,764 --> 00:06:40,581
and, obviously,
it's gotten worse.

114
00:06:40,684 --> 00:06:43,195
- Much worse.
- - This is the nurse's button.

115
00:06:43,219 --> 00:06:45,770
If you need anything, you
push it. I mean, push it a lot.

116
00:06:45,872 --> 00:06:50,174
Don't worry about being annoying.
Push it till they come in here.

117
00:06:53,030 --> 00:06:56,347
It's OK. It's all right. Here.

118
00:07:00,187 --> 00:07:01,986
Not too loud, OK?

119
00:07:02,089 --> 00:07:05,524
<i>It happens more than you'd think,
having to do a procedure on a kid</i>

120
00:07:05,626 --> 00:07:08,794
<i>with no parents around. Some of
these kids are in here for weeks.</i>

121
00:07:08,896 --> 00:07:12,097
Their parents usually can't
take off that much work.

122
00:07:12,198 --> 00:07:13,932
But, I mean, we try to help out.

123
00:07:14,034 --> 00:07:18,136
We have these beds, we call them
parent cots, for the parents to sleep in.

124
00:07:18,238 --> 00:07:20,639
But a lot of these kids
spend a lot of time alone.

125
00:07:20,741 --> 00:07:23,675
Just works out that way.
Doesn't mean they're bad parents,

126
00:07:23,777 --> 00:07:27,145
they're just busy parents.

127
00:07:27,230 --> 00:07:30,782
I found out last
night that he...

128
00:07:30,884 --> 00:07:34,102
had been in an accident.

129
00:07:36,306 --> 00:07:41,526
Just before the phone rang,
I had this sinking feeling.

130
00:07:41,628 --> 00:07:43,761
Motorcycles.

131
00:07:45,032 --> 00:07:49,000
Donor cycles. Isn't
that what they call them?

132
00:07:49,102 --> 00:07:51,736
<i>They called me in here because
even though Sam is a donor,</i>

133
00:07:51,839 --> 00:07:56,708
<i>they need special consent
for something like this.</i>

134
00:07:56,810 --> 00:08:01,095
I know Sam would want to donate
whatever he could so, of course, yes.

135
00:08:01,197 --> 00:08:04,549
They can... They
can take his arms.

136
00:08:04,651 --> 00:08:08,269
Absolutely. I have
no problem with that.

137
00:08:10,790 --> 00:08:16,728
Although... it's hard.

138
00:08:18,498 --> 00:08:22,366
The thought of somebody
else... holding his hand.

139
00:08:24,938 --> 00:08:26,605
See that? That
could be a problem.

140
00:08:26,707 --> 00:08:29,541
What if we try a bypass instead?

141
00:08:30,611 --> 00:08:33,461
<i>Derek and I? We go way back.</i>

142
00:08:33,563 --> 00:08:36,931
<i>We grew up together, we
went to med school together.</i>

143
00:08:37,033 --> 00:08:40,885
He's... he's kinda
like my better half.

144
00:08:40,987 --> 00:08:44,188
Not the better-looking
half, mind you.

145
00:08:46,125 --> 00:08:48,459
So when I heard he got shot...

146
00:08:54,434 --> 00:08:58,235
Every day we give
bad news to patients.

147
00:08:58,337 --> 00:09:01,739
We tell them their
loved ones are hurt,

148
00:09:01,841 --> 00:09:05,176
or dying, or dead.

149
00:09:09,015 --> 00:09:13,150
And for the first time in my life,
I understood what that feels like.

150
00:09:15,655 --> 00:09:17,254
Feels like...

151
00:09:17,356 --> 00:09:19,157
No, no. You're thinking
like a nerve guy.

152
00:09:19,259 --> 00:09:21,204
- I am a nerve guy.
- It goes blood supply,
then nerves.

153
00:09:21,228 --> 00:09:23,039
Actually, it's tendons, then
blood supply, then nerves.

154
00:09:23,063 --> 00:09:25,496
Um, hello? What about the bones?

155
00:09:25,598 --> 00:09:28,199
That's certainly something
to take into consideration...

156
00:09:28,302 --> 00:09:33,605
Um, we estimate the surgery will
take anywhere from 15 to 20 hours.

157
00:09:33,707 --> 00:09:38,677
We'll have two ORs going at once.
There'll be five teams of surgeons.

158
00:09:38,779 --> 00:09:41,674
One team for each arm, and then a
fifth just to harvest veins from the leg.

159
00:09:41,698 --> 00:09:44,982
You know there's only been one
successful bilateral arm transplant

160
00:09:45,084 --> 00:09:46,729
- in the country. In the world.
- In the world.

161
00:09:46,753 --> 00:09:50,187
I wouldn't go so far as
calling us medical titans, but...

162
00:09:50,290 --> 00:09:52,802
- We are.
- - Not the first time I've been called a titan.

163
00:09:52,826 --> 00:09:55,960
Uh, right now I am prepping

164
00:09:56,062 --> 00:10:00,197
the donor body to extract
antibodies from his blood.

165
00:10:00,299 --> 00:10:01,877
This is all in
preparation for later,

166
00:10:01,901 --> 00:10:06,170
when we'll remove, uh,
bone marrow from the donor.

167
00:10:06,272 --> 00:10:10,174
And then we'll infuse the marrow
into Zack to reduce the chances

168
00:10:10,276 --> 00:10:14,462
of his body rejecting
the arms, which is huge.

169
00:10:14,564 --> 00:10:16,297
More than huge.

170
00:10:16,399 --> 00:10:19,717
I mean, I'm no
medical Titan, but...

171
00:10:19,819 --> 00:10:22,721
still, it's pretty damn cool.

172
00:10:22,823 --> 00:10:27,191
Uh, yeah, Zack lost his arms four
years ago. It was an accident at work.

173
00:10:27,293 --> 00:10:31,096
He is... uh, he was a logger.

174
00:10:31,197 --> 00:10:33,564
So it could have gone
either way. I mean,

175
00:10:33,666 --> 00:10:36,400
this thing could have come
between us, or it could have

176
00:10:36,502 --> 00:10:43,141
brought us closer together. And
for us, I think it's brought us closer.

177
00:10:43,243 --> 00:10:45,088
Literally. I have to
wipe his... for him.

178
00:10:45,112 --> 00:10:47,045
OK, really?

179
00:10:47,147 --> 00:10:49,225
That's what you want to talk
about in front of everyone right now?

180
00:10:49,249 --> 00:10:51,449
- I do.
- I'm sorry.

181
00:10:51,551 --> 00:10:53,885
I'd cover my face, but
I don't have any hands.

182
00:10:56,572 --> 00:11:01,910
- You been good since I last saw you?
- - Busy.

183
00:11:02,011 --> 00:11:04,428
Bill and I left town
right after the shooting,

184
00:11:04,530 --> 00:11:07,948
and pretty much
never looked back.

185
00:11:08,050 --> 00:11:11,268
So far, we've been to Paris,

186
00:11:11,370 --> 00:11:15,907
Morocco, Alaska, a
cruise through the Baltic.

187
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:18,475
- What?
- Blew through our savings, but,

188
00:11:18,578 --> 00:11:22,580
- hey, life is short, right?
- Sure is.

189
00:11:24,601 --> 00:11:29,687
Is there anything I'm looking
forward to once my surgery is done?

190
00:11:31,424 --> 00:11:33,457
Babies.

191
00:11:33,559 --> 00:11:35,993
Lots and lots of babies.

192
00:11:36,096 --> 00:11:38,629
Deep breath. Another.

193
00:11:38,731 --> 00:11:41,432
<i>Enter security access code.</i>

194
00:11:46,456 --> 00:11:49,690
- You're sure?
- I'm sure. I'm sure. I'm sure.

195
00:11:49,792 --> 00:11:53,027
- I'm sure.
<i>- Enter security...</i>

196
00:11:53,129 --> 00:11:55,946
There are some kinks with
the new security system.

197
00:11:56,048 --> 00:12:01,118
But there are always kinks
when something... new.

198
00:12:01,220 --> 00:12:03,488
But we're working them out.

199
00:12:03,590 --> 00:12:08,126
<i>We got this, um, new
state-of-the-art like, lockdown system...</i>

200
00:12:08,228 --> 00:12:12,279
<i>To isolate different areas of the
hospital in case of an emergency.</i>

201
00:12:12,382 --> 00:12:16,333
'Cause, um, supposedly,
the last emergency, there were

202
00:12:16,436 --> 00:12:20,037
some people wandering around.

203
00:12:20,139 --> 00:12:24,425
Even with the kinks, I think
people feel safer, which is important.

204
00:12:27,364 --> 00:12:30,131
Uh, sorry to interrupt,
chief. I just... I got your page,

205
00:12:30,233 --> 00:12:33,434
- but, hey, I can come back.
- Oh, nonsense.

206
00:12:33,537 --> 00:12:37,705
Congratulations. I just heard the
big news, and I am so proud of you.

207
00:12:37,807 --> 00:12:42,476
- Ah...
- Uh, our very
own Dr. Robbins here

208
00:12:42,579 --> 00:12:45,979
has been awarded the
prestigious Carter Madison Grant.

209
00:12:46,082 --> 00:12:48,282
<i>Yeah, I haven't told
that many people yet.</i>

210
00:12:48,384 --> 00:12:51,602
A Carter Madison Grant? Nobody
wins those. I mean, nobody normal.

211
00:12:51,704 --> 00:12:54,906
Just those brainy scientist types
who are from Germany and Sweden.

212
00:12:55,008 --> 00:12:59,476
- Oh, my God! You won! Are you kidding?
- Nope. She is not kidding.

213
00:12:59,578 --> 00:13:01,478
- Come here!
- Oh, thank you.

214
00:13:01,580 --> 00:13:04,093
<i>No, I didn't apply for the
grant because of the shooting.</i>

215
00:13:04,117 --> 00:13:08,202
There are major gaps in the care
of children in developing countries.

216
00:13:08,304 --> 00:13:11,606
Global health initiatives
exist for things like malaria,

217
00:13:11,708 --> 00:13:15,476
uh, infectious diseases, immunizations,
but not for pediatric surgery.

218
00:13:15,578 --> 00:13:18,930
With this grant, I could
start to change that.

219
00:13:19,032 --> 00:13:20,948
Well, I applied for this
thing two years ago.

220
00:13:21,050 --> 00:13:23,451
I was a completely
different person.

221
00:13:23,553 --> 00:13:27,722
I was new here,
um, a surgical fellow,

222
00:13:27,823 --> 00:13:29,156
single.

223
00:13:29,259 --> 00:13:32,977
<i>But now I have people
here, important people.</i>

224
00:13:33,079 --> 00:13:36,230
<i>Which complicates things.</i>

225
00:13:36,332 --> 00:13:41,752
<i>But this is bigger than me. This
