457
00:29:21,226 --> 00:29:22,559
Avery...

458
00:29:24,396 --> 00:29:28,131
You can stop now.
Someone else can take over.

459
00:29:28,233 --> 00:29:31,835
Avery, look at me. Look
at me. You can stop now.

460
00:29:31,937 --> 00:29:34,955
Avery, Avery. It's OK, it's OK.

461
00:29:42,698 --> 00:29:47,667
<i>It's been, uh... hard
since the shooting.</i>

462
00:29:50,572 --> 00:29:54,541
I, uh... I lost some
friends that day.

463
00:29:59,415 --> 00:30:02,432
<i>You learn to think
about things differently.</i>

464
00:30:02,534 --> 00:30:06,986
Like, um, buttoning a
button. You can't do that,

465
00:30:07,088 --> 00:30:12,125
you know, even with the hooks,
so... you know, I just buy Zack t-shirts

466
00:30:12,227 --> 00:30:14,093
and hoodies.

467
00:30:14,195 --> 00:30:19,299
He can usually get those on by
himself, by using his hooks and his feet.

468
00:30:20,201 --> 00:30:23,136
I help him bathe in the morning,

469
00:30:23,238 --> 00:30:28,007
and brush his teeth and shave.

470
00:30:28,109 --> 00:30:32,245
It took me a long time
to get the hang of that.

471
00:30:32,347 --> 00:30:35,582
But it's all in the
wrist, I've learned.

472
00:30:38,137 --> 00:30:42,305
And it's late.

473
00:30:42,408 --> 00:30:46,776
I thought I would
have an update by now.

474
00:30:46,878 --> 00:30:49,246
So, what's the big deal?
You'll visit her, she'll visit you.

475
00:30:49,348 --> 00:30:52,299
- It's just a plane ride.
- Um, can we not talk
about this right now?

476
00:30:52,401 --> 00:30:56,319
- Arm's getting cyanotic.
- - The vessel attachments are all good.

477
00:31:00,809 --> 00:31:03,521
- Picture. We got picture and no sound.
- Excuse me?

478
00:31:03,545 --> 00:31:06,246
Move over. Just move over.

479
00:31:24,766 --> 00:31:26,666
Any update?

480
00:31:28,504 --> 00:31:31,505
- What? Just tell me.
- Um...

481
00:31:31,607 --> 00:31:36,376
There was a possible
complication with one of the arms.

482
00:31:36,478 --> 00:31:38,111
Complication?

483
00:31:38,213 --> 00:31:44,050
There's a clot and they're
trying to restore blood flow, but...

484
00:31:45,554 --> 00:31:47,754
He could lose it, couldn't he?

485
00:31:54,863 --> 00:31:57,531
One arm is better
than none, right?

486
00:32:02,237 --> 00:32:04,917
- Do you need help?
- - I could retract that for you.

487
00:32:04,990 --> 00:32:06,635
- You want me to patch that?
- Gimme a second.

488
00:32:06,659 --> 00:32:09,237
- Are you sure
you don't want me...
- Give me a second!

489
00:32:09,261 --> 00:32:12,301
I know what I'm doing. I just
need a second. Everybody shut up.

490
00:32:21,372 --> 00:32:24,157
OK. All right. There.
Picture and sound.

491
00:32:24,259 --> 00:32:26,125
I think.

492
00:32:49,534 --> 00:32:53,102
- That's good. Nicely done.
- Perfect.

493
00:32:53,205 --> 00:32:56,756
<i>Basically, we break the
cartilage down to a cellular level</i>

494
00:32:56,858 --> 00:32:58,591
<i>and turn it into
a protein liquid.</i>

495
00:32:58,693 --> 00:33:01,794
<i>We build a scaffolding
to hold the liquid.</i>

496
00:33:01,896 --> 00:33:04,580
<i>And we cook it in an
incubator to let it grow.</i>

497
00:33:04,682 --> 00:33:08,034
This is the incubator. We're
gonna grow the trachea in here first.

498
00:33:08,136 --> 00:33:12,038
Then, once it's big enough, we're
gonna insert it into Lily's abdomen

499
00:33:12,140 --> 00:33:14,524
till it gets stronger. It'll
be there a few months.

500
00:33:14,626 --> 00:33:17,794
Then we'll take that new
trachea and replace her old one.

501
00:33:17,896 --> 00:33:22,115
Some might say that a
shooting would set people back,

502
00:33:22,217 --> 00:33:24,750
then you look at
residents like Dr. Karev,

503
00:33:24,852 --> 00:33:30,090
and attendings like Dr. Robbins,
and you see their innovative thinking,

504
00:33:30,192 --> 00:33:36,129
their resilience. You see them
becoming reinvested in medicine.

505
00:33:38,833 --> 00:33:41,033
It's inspiring, isn't it?

506
00:33:45,090 --> 00:33:48,825
I've mobilized the two
intestinal segments,

507
00:33:48,927 --> 00:33:52,729
and I've stapled, and...

508
00:33:54,366 --> 00:33:56,466
that's it. Textbook.

509
00:33:56,568 --> 00:33:59,502
In and out in an hour.

510
00:34:02,507 --> 00:34:04,708
Time to close.

511
00:34:08,547 --> 00:34:12,515
It went well. Mary's being
wheeled into recovery right now.

512
00:34:12,618 --> 00:34:16,185
- So it's over?
- It's over.

513
00:34:16,288 --> 00:34:18,622
Oh, God.

514
00:34:19,258 --> 00:34:20,435
- Oh, thank you.
- Oh!

515
00:34:20,459 --> 00:34:22,292
Thank you.

516
00:34:23,628 --> 00:34:25,762
Thank you.

517
00:34:25,864 --> 00:34:27,597
Oh!

518
00:34:27,699 --> 00:34:31,834
<i>This is one surgery I am
happy to have finished.</i>

519
00:34:31,936 --> 00:34:34,387
<i>Tonight?</i>

520
00:34:34,489 --> 00:34:37,140
<i>I may very well
take the night off.</i>

521
00:34:37,242 --> 00:34:43,295
Go out. Maybe have
a drink. Who knows?

522
00:34:45,099 --> 00:34:48,735
Oh! Gentlemen and lady,
we gave a man arms today.

523
00:34:48,837 --> 00:34:50,670
- All right.
- I think of it more as I gave

524
00:34:50,772 --> 00:34:52,383
a man arms today, the
rest of you just helped.

525
00:34:52,407 --> 00:34:54,552
Another round for
everybody but my friend here.

526
00:34:54,576 --> 00:34:56,120
That's a nice shirt, by the
way. Where'd you get that?

527
00:34:56,144 --> 00:34:58,411
- The special Titan store?
- You saw the way she saved

528
00:34:58,514 --> 00:35:00,257
that arm today? You wanna
hear something funny?

529
00:35:00,281 --> 00:35:03,416
She hooked up my TV, I'm still
only getting sound out of one speaker.

530
00:35:06,354 --> 00:35:09,689
<i>So I'll have to irrigate the
trachea with this protein mixture</i>

531
00:35:09,808 --> 00:35:12,692
a few times a day every
day for the next few weeks.

532
00:35:14,029 --> 00:35:16,529
<i>Which means I'll pretty
much be living in this hospital</i>

533
00:35:16,648 --> 00:35:18,781
<i>to make sure it gets done right.</i>

534
00:35:20,134 --> 00:35:23,770
<i>That's my priority, is to
make sure this trachea grows.</i>

535
00:35:24,673 --> 00:35:26,873
<i>And it's my focus.</i>

536
00:35:26,975 --> 00:35:31,894
<i>I'll basically be eating, breathing and
sleeping trachea for the next month.</i>

537
00:35:31,996 --> 00:35:34,597
Do people treat me differently
now, after the shooting?

538
00:35:34,699 --> 00:35:39,518
Uh, well... Um, I mean, yeah.
You're here filming me, so...

539
00:35:39,621 --> 00:35:42,388
I mean, people like to say what
I did was heroic, but it wasn't.

540
00:35:42,490 --> 00:35:46,793
It was just a thing I had to do. I
think people like to have a hero.

541
00:35:46,895 --> 00:35:50,396
And it makes them feel better,

542
00:35:50,498 --> 00:35:54,684
to think that there in the
middle of all that horror,

543
00:35:54,786 --> 00:35:58,872
that there's someone special
working medical miracles.

544
00:35:58,973 --> 00:36:03,610
But... I...

545
00:36:03,712 --> 00:36:07,280
I mean, I don't have
super surgical powers.

546
00:36:07,382 --> 00:36:09,282
I mean, I'm... I did what...

547
00:36:09,384 --> 00:36:12,151
Cristina is a hero.

548
00:36:12,253 --> 00:36:14,270
Especially to me.

549
00:36:14,372 --> 00:36:17,507
The truth is, is most surgeons

550
00:36:17,609 --> 00:36:20,677
could not have done
what she did that day.

551
00:36:20,779 --> 00:36:23,296
- If you had seen...
- Stop it.

552
00:36:26,301 --> 00:36:28,341
- If you had seen...
- Stop. Please, just can you...

553
00:36:28,403 --> 00:36:30,503
Can you just stop this?

554
00:36:35,844 --> 00:36:37,810
Can we cut?

555
00:36:44,485 --> 00:36:46,819
Just doing a
little construction.

556
00:36:46,921 --> 00:36:49,856
Things are always
evolving around here.

557
00:36:49,958 --> 00:36:53,626
For the better.
Always for the better.

558
00:36:53,728 --> 00:36:56,763
Whoa! Hey!

559
00:36:56,865 --> 00:36:59,331
- How'd you let that happen?
- I don't know.

560
00:36:59,433 --> 00:37:02,001
- You get it cleaned up.
- You guys all right?

561
00:37:02,103 --> 00:37:03,235
Hey, let me give you a hand.

562
00:37:04,740 --> 00:37:08,240
Yeah, he already has some feeling
at the tops of his new arms. Look.

563
00:37:08,343 --> 00:37:11,511
Ow! Watch this.

564
00:37:15,016 --> 00:37:16,449
Not bad, huh?

565
00:37:18,236 --> 00:37:20,003
Look, right there.

566
00:37:20,105 --> 00:37:24,107
You can barely even see a scar
where they put the tube in last month.

567
00:37:24,209 --> 00:37:28,177
And now I'm back today to get
my new trachea sewn into my belly.

568
00:37:28,280 --> 00:37:30,963
Dr. Karev calls me
the human incubator.

569
00:37:31,065 --> 00:37:35,651
He's been sending me photos
from the lab of my new trachea.

570
00:37:37,322 --> 00:37:39,655
See? Look at that right there.

571
00:37:41,026 --> 00:37:43,692
It's really grown.

572
00:37:43,795 --> 00:37:46,129
See, right there...

573
00:37:46,231 --> 00:37:48,614
I always figured I'd
grow up to be a rock star,

574
00:37:48,716 --> 00:37:52,986
but I might consider
being a doctor now, too.

575
00:37:53,088 --> 00:37:56,655
I mean, Dr. Karev
is pretty cool.

576
00:37:56,758 --> 00:38:00,726
Check it out.
Home-grown trachea.

577
00:38:03,598 --> 00:38:08,868
Whatever you do, just don't screw
around and mess up my trachea, OK?

578
00:38:08,970 --> 00:38:12,939
I mean it. I know you think
you're a rock star, but no mosh pits

579
00:38:13,041 --> 00:38:17,294
or crowd surfing. I mean,
Lilith Fair is OK, but...

580
00:38:17,396 --> 00:38:21,647
No drinking or drugs or
smoking or driving drunk

581
00:38:21,750 --> 00:38:24,601
or giving your number
out to guys you don't know.

582
00:38:24,703 --> 00:38:26,703
Um...

583
00:38:26,805 --> 00:38:30,073
You get that I'm nine?

584
00:38:46,941 --> 00:38:49,101
<i>Well, I really can't believe it.</i>

585
00:38:49,127 --> 00:38:51,828
<i>The big move to Africa is
really just around the corner.</i>

586
00:38:51,930 --> 00:38:54,747
Yes, I would say things
are better between us now.

587
00:38:54,849 --> 00:38:58,951
And yes, we worked it out, even
with Arizona moving to Africa.

588
00:38:59,053 --> 00:39:02,855
The fix was, uh, pretty simple,
actually. I'm going with her.

589
00:39:10,531 --> 00:39:13,633
Got you some new flowers. Um...

590
00:39:13,735 --> 00:39:17,169
Yellow ones today, um,
don't ask me what kind.

591
00:39:17,271 --> 00:39:20,573
I have no idea.

592
00:39:28,617 --> 00:39:31,150
They're, uh...
they're pretty, though.

593
00:39:31,820 --> 00:39:33,886
Just like you.

594
00:39:36,491 --> 00:39:42,144
It's rare, but sometimes patients
do not wake up from surgery.

595
00:39:42,247 --> 00:39:44,347
With every surgery,
there is a risk.

596
00:39:44,449 --> 00:39:47,733
In this case, the
post operative CT

597
00:39:47,835 --> 00:39:51,387
showed no sign of
stroke, no acute bleed.

598
00:39:51,489 --> 00:39:54,757
We've run PET scans, MRIs,

599
00:39:54,859 --> 00:39:57,059
tried fluids, pressors.

600
00:39:57,161 --> 00:40:01,914
Basically, that's what I have to
go and talk to Bill about today.

601
00:40:02,017 --> 00:40:04,750
Mary has been in a
coma since her surgery.

602
00:40:04,853 --> 00:40:07,637
There's no sign
of brain activity,

603
00:40:07,739 --> 00:40:12,391
and now she's septic.
Her organs are failing.

604
00:40:12,493 --> 00:40:15,612
Best-case scenario...

605
00:40:15,714 --> 00:40:18,848
um, she'd regain some function

606
00:40:18,950 --> 00:40:22,652
and wakes up with extreme
deficits, mentally and physically.

607
00:40:22,754 --> 00:40:28,557
But the chance of her
waking up at this point...

608
00:40:32,931 --> 00:40:37,784
It's hard. To imagine someone
surviving a crazy gunman,

609
00:40:37,886 --> 00:40:40,386
and then not to survive
such a simple surgery.

610
00:40:40,488 --> 00:40:45,141
<i>I have to go and
tell Bill that it's time.</i>

611
00:40:48,596 --> 00:40:51,130
<i>He has a decision to make.</i>

612
00:41:17,108 --> 00:41:18,942
Hi.

613
00:41:22,597 --> 00:41:26,566
We went through the scariest thing a
person can go through, and we survived.

614
00:41:26,667 --> 00:41:30,202
<i>So now, every
day is just a gift.</i>

615
00:41:30,304 --> 00:41:33,272
<i>And we're all just blessed.</i>

616
00:41:35,259 --> 00:41:37,026
<i>Blessed to be here,</i>

617
00:41:37,128 --> 00:41:39,195
<i>blessed to be doing
what we do best,</i>

618
00:41:39,297 --> 00:41:41,981
<i>which is saving lives.</i>

619
00:41:44,019 --> 00:41:45,735
<i>Every day.</i>

620
00:41:49,291 --> 00:41:52,091
<i>One life at a time.</i>

621
00:41:54,295 --> 00:41:56,412
<i>We're healed,</i>

622
00:41:56,514 --> 00:42:00,450
<i>so we can continue
healing others.</i>

623
00:42:00,552 --> 00:42:05,154
Is there any one thing you'll
take away from all of this?

624
00:42:11,062 --> 00:42:13,563
Being a hero has its price.
